<div id="review_2754868340" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2754868340" />
    <a title="J.M. Hushour" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/17463213-j-m-hushour"><img alt="J.M. Hushour" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442964894p2/17463213.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2754868340?book_show_action=true">Mar 20, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="J.M. Hushour" class="user" itemprop="url" name="J.M. Hushour" href="/user/show/17463213-j-m-hushour">J.M. Hushour</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780895267689" href="/book/show/762477.The_Three_Cornered_World">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2754868340" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6602286125218207650">&quot;I am the sort of person who can never become a true artist as long as he is having his farts counted by detectives.&quot;<br/><br/>A delightfully untroubled artist wanders around a hot-spring inn in rural Japan musing on the nature of art while verbally and sexually sparring with the innkeeper&apos;s daughter. A bit of a lazy ass, the narrator does his best to remove himself from the crappy modern world so that he can get a poetic grip on the shaft of Nature. The crazy-ass innkeeper&apos;s daughter, divorced and return</span>
  <span id="freeText6602286125218207650" style="display:none">"I am the sort of person who can never become a true artist as long as he is having his farts counted by detectives."<br /><br />A delightfully untroubled artist wanders around a hot-spring inn in rural Japan musing on the nature of art while verbally and sexually sparring with the innkeeper's daughter. A bit of a lazy ass, the narrator does his best to remove himself from the crappy modern world so that he can get a poetic grip on the shaft of Nature. The crazy-ass innkeeper's daughter, divorced and returned to the countryside where she wanders verandahs with possible daggers and shows up naked at the worst/best possible moments, eludes the artist as a subject for his art (and his heart).<br />At all times sublime and potentially disturbing, nothing really turns out as you think it might. Another profound Soseki meditation on who we are and what the hell we are doing.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6602286125218207650" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


