<div id="review_3338028635" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3338028635" />
    <a title="Quentin Tan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/60468831-quentin-tan"><img alt="Quentin Tan" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3338028635?book_show_action=true">May 15, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Quentin Tan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Quentin Tan" href="/user/show/60468831-quentin-tan">Quentin Tan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780143105190" href="/book/show/1776113.Kusamakura">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/60468831-quentin-tan?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3338028635" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12540190928502844475">Fledgling artists often <s>commit the sin</s> fall into the trap of calling anything that&apos;s remotely poignant and short &quot;haiku-esque.&quot; But they could not be more correct if they attached that worn-out adjective to their description of Natsume Sōseki&apos;s <i>Kusamakura</i>, which happens to be his fifth work that I have had the fortune of reading.<br/><br/>In writing Kusamakura, or more well-known in the Anglophone world, if at all, as <i>The Three-Cornered World</i>, Sōseki writes that his intention had been to write a &quot;haiku-st</span>
  <span id="freeText12540190928502844475" style="display:none">Fledgling artists often <s>commit the sin</s> fall into the trap of calling anything that's remotely poignant and short "haiku-esque." But they could not be more correct if they attached that worn-out adjective to their description of Natsume Sōseki's <i>Kusamakura</i>, which happens to be his fifth work that I have had the fortune of reading.<br /><br />In writing Kusamakura, or more well-known in the Anglophone world, if at all, as <i>The Three-Cornered World</i>, Sōseki writes that his intention had been to write a "haiku-style novel", one that aims to and only to impart "a certain feeling, a feeling of beauty" to the reader; the novel concerns itself not with notions of "plot" or "development of events" accustomed to our ordinary sensibilities. <br /><br />This work, "in almost every way an anomaly, in terms both of Sōseki's work and of the modern Japanese novel", can be read as the great novelist's elaboration and development of his ideals as an artist and a profoundly unique aesthetic consciousness, firmly embedded in the philosophical terrains of a young Meiji Japan. Above all, <i>Kusamakura</i> represents Sōseki's extraordinary response to a necessary stage that all aspiring writers must pass through - the development of an artistic vision inseparable from the strictures of our time and place.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12540190928502844475" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


